Votre phrase est déjà bonne, mais on peut l’améliorer légèrement pour refléter précisément ce que vous venez de dire :
👉 le problème est apparu entre le 15 février et le 20 février (date des premières erreurs).
Voici une version corrigée et plus précise pour votre mail RCA :
The last successful RPM transaction recorded on the system corresponds to DNF transaction ID 140, executed on February 15 at 19:34. This transaction completed successfully and involved updates to several system packages including poppler, cups components, net-snmp, openssl, libpng, and gnupg2. The timestamps of the RPM database files confirm that the database was last modified at that time.
However, the first RPM database errors were observed in the system logs starting on February 20. This indicates that the RPM database corruption most likely occurred between February 15 (after the last successful transaction) and February 20 (when the first database errors appeared).
As a result, the kernel patching operation performed on March 8 did not trigger the corruption but instead exposed the existing inconsistency when the package manager attempted to access the RPM database.
Cette version est meilleure parce qu’elle montre clairement :
✔ dernière transaction RPM
✔ fenêtre de corruption (15 → 20 février)
✔ le patch kernel n’est pas la cause
✔ analyse basée sur les logs.
